I have a mother that loves words, and thus I have grown up surrounded
by books. My mother spent several thousand dollars that she didn't have
on a Catholic school for me and my brother so that we could avoid whole
language. Through this and her obvious passion for the written word,
she has imparted a deep understanding and love for literature and our
language into my brother and me. I spent my english classes identifying
independent clauses and diagraming sentences, and this joined my love
with and understanding.
While avoiding whole language could only be a benifit, is has hardly
paid off in droves. It has not made me into a better man or improved my
sex life dramatically, but I have become a better writer and
communicatior as a result. Additionally, I think that as society moves
towards more streamlining and less understanding, we move deeper and
deeper into a soceity dominated by mindless drones.
I can definatly say that the love for literature has dyed out,
especially among my peers. I'm a high school junior, and I know only a
handful of people with whom I can hold a literary discussion. A
frightenly large percentage of my classmates don't even recgonize
titles like War and Peace and Othello, works once universaly known, if
not read. Again, society moves away from knowledge to efficancy, and
the thinking man's position in the world drops another rung.

