Hi Rosewood, is the controversy between phonics and whole language
really the big issue? Hasn't school as an institute has moved away from
education towards entertainment, fun and baby-sitting?

How do students get familiar with words? Right, by using them. The more
you read, write, talk and listen, the more you become fluent in any
language and the more you gain understanding of words and grasp and
appreciate the full meaning of subtleties. The key is to use language -
the more you are confonted with words, search for that one word that
says exactly what you mean, the more your grammar and verbiosity will
improve.

But what's happening at school? Children sit there, expecting to be
entertained by a teacher who - in an desperate attempt to oblige -
writes the word DINOSAURS on the blackboard. This week, we'll have
dinosaurs agaion as a theme!

Should a teacher write: di·no·saur ( P ) Pronunciation Key
(dn-sôr) n. - extinct, often gigantic, carnivorous or herbivorous
reptiles of the orders Saurischia and Ornithischia; they were chiefly
terrestrial and existed during the Mesozoic Era. [New Latin Dnosauria,
group name, from Dnosaurus, former genus name : Greek deinos,
monstrous + Greek sauros, lizard.]

Or should a teacher draw a dinosaur on the blackboard and tell the
children to all make such a drawing?

My view is that - to improve literacy levels- children should simply
start reading and writing and it doesn't matter much what they're
reading and writing about, they can read and write about dinosaurs or
anything else, as long as they start reading and writing. Once you
start with that, you'll improve and if you can get feedback and
guidence, all the better, but the ley is to do it!

I think it's not so much a controversy between phonics and whole
language, but it's a question of teachers that educate or teachers that
don't. Just my 2 cents. Anyone else?

