I understand your thoughts regarding teachers being entertainers and
babysitters, many people who have not spent much time in a classroom
feel this way.

As a teacher, I spend many hours devoted to teaching students not only
to read, but to understand what it is they are reading. I have
comprehension competitions, give out rewards just for completing books,
and spend a great deal of time allowing children to share their
enthusiasm for specific books in the classroom. My junior high
students read an average of three novels per month (more reading than
many adults).
Writing is not neglected either in my classes. We focus on content,
grammer, and penmanship, something that seems to be a dying cause with
the influx of computers. I mark 16 hours every second weekend, at the
expense of time with my family, but former students have come back to
tell me the difference I have made in their lives, and how much easier
High School seems to be because they know how to write an essay, or
they can understand the structure of the stories they read.

Children will not just start to read and write on their own. They need
motivation. Parents and community need to support the push for more
literacy and spend time in the schools reading to kids. Imagine if all
stakeholders cared enough about the learning of children to spend time
reading to kids, or listening to a child's story, instead of placing
that responsibility solely on the shoulders of a teacher. What a
wonderful world it would be.
AA

